From b65161316fdd434d090f50dd527aee0476138b3f Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Gautham Kumar Senthilkumaran <gauthamk@qti.qualcomm.com>
Date: Thu, 25 Sep 2025 11:26:21 +0530
Subject: [PATCH] UPSTREAM:CP: wifi:ath12k: Fix destroying the rhashtable for
 stale entries

Currently, arsta is maintained in a rhashtable, which is used to fetch
the entry using the station address as the key. During Mode 0 recovery,
the host sends disassociation frames to all peers connected to the AP.
After sending disassoc, it removes entries from the rhashtable one by
one using the station list from mac80211. In one instance, arsta was
freed but not removed from the rhashtable.

This causes a stale entry to remain in the table, eventually leading to
corruption of the rhashtable and a crash. Such stale entries are
dangerous and must be handled properly to maintain the integrity of the
data structure and ensure system stability during recovery operations.

To fix this, if a stale entry is found in the rhashtable, the entire
table is destroyed and reinitialized to store fresh arsta entries.
This prevents corruption, clears stale entries, and ensures the
rhashtable remains in a consistent and stable state.

Patch-dependency:
0241-0002-wifi-ath12k-WDS-subsystem-recovery-fix.patch

Signed-off-by: Gautham Kumar Senthilkumaran <gauthamk@qti.qualcomm.com>

--- a/drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath12k/mac.c
+++ b/drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath12k/mac.c
@@ -1511,6 +1511,15 @@ void ath12k_mac_peer_cleanup_all(struct
 					  ath12k_mac_link_sta_rhash_cleanup,
 					  ar);
 
+	/* The rhash table should be empty after cleanup
+	 */
+	if (atomic_read(&ab->rhead_sta_addr->nelems)) {
+		ath12k_warn(ab,
+			    "Destroying rhash table and has stale entries %d\n",
+			    atomic_read(&ab->rhead_sta_addr->nelems));
+		ath12k_link_sta_rhash_tbl_destroy(ab);
+		ath12k_link_sta_rhash_tbl_init(ab);
+	}
 	/* Delete all the self dp_peers on asserted radio
 	 */
 	list_for_each_entry_safe_reverse(arvif, tmp_vif, &ar->arvifs, list) {
